Text:
@logitech4873 Interesting ideas, but we are firmly in a Carbon deficient point in Earth's temperature cycle.  I suggest you review the estimated global average temperatures for the last 500 million years, particularly the Cretaceous Thermal Maximum period.

How does Earth's current biomass compare to warmer periods?

Man-caused climate change is more religion than science.

@diggernash1 I think you fail to understand the issue. Nobody's saying that a higher carbon atmosphere is a bad thing in isolation, but the rapid change is the issue. All flora and fauna ecosystems on Earth has adapted to the current state of the climate. Changes in the climate usually happen over millions of years, but today we're causing the same changes to happen in just HUNDREDS of years.

Also, higher carbon periods always had very large deserts near the equator. The US would be a desert if we had carbon levels similar to the carboniferous period.

Manmade accelerated global warming is extremely well established science. But maybe you're like a flat earther or something.

@logitech4873I almost always rent a vehicle for long distance trips. 

1. Keeps the miles off you POV. 
2. Lowers personal liability. If I crash a rental in BFE, I don’t have to go back and get it.

@logitech4873 Yep, yep. Still I'd say my understanding is reflective of a broad misunderstanding among most average consumers deciding whether or not to be EVs. There needs to be more work done on educating people and expanding infrastructure, especially infrastructure for level 2 charging to be done cheaply by people who can't charge at home. 

Well that and manufacturers need to make it so these battery replacement horror stories stop cropping up. The only EV that can have it's battery replaced at a price that's even halfway toward not putting people in financial ruin is the battery on a Nissan Leaf. That's not acceptable, there needs to stop being wild headlines about EV battery replacements costing anywhere from 15 to 60 thousand dollars.

Oh yeah and there was also that insane news story out of Scotland about a family who drove their Tesla in the rain only for the service center to blame them for water damage and try to charge them 30 thousand dollars for a new battery.

@jamess1314 They do in case more manpower is needed somewhere due to a disaster. And what if infrastructure/ energy grid is damaged or far away? Each hour pumps operate that's a lot of power. Just because something is fine for doing round trips in a city doesn't mean it will be sufficient for emergency services.
They can go hybrid or hydrogen-electric or whatever but not 100% electric. Maybe with battery hot-swap technology or mobile generators, but that would require additional vehicles.
And does it even matter? Overall emissions from fire engines compared to car/ truck/ plane emissions is like 0.00000001%

@tomsd8656 Converting energy from one form to another comes at great loss of efficiency.  Porting that power to an outlet causes massive transmission losses.  I don't think the EV is really saving much, except it's moving the fossil fuel consumption away from the vehicle, which is good for city air, but not moving the needle for the planet.

I agree that hybrid tech is VERY promising. Good power and ridiculously good gas mileage, plus, if you keep your driving to a minimum as I do, you can do a lot of good with a pretty cheap solar panel.

The main "benefit" of pure EV is it restricts the mobility of common people.

@pato6672 Huh? Do people that hate EV's spend time to think of ridiculous replies like this?

You think that someone is going to come along and chop a cable with 240V and 50 amps? I don't think so.

The cables are attached to the charger and in most cars are locked to the car until the car is either fully charged or past a certain percentage - a feature put into cars so that if someone is charging at a station and they don't come back when the car is fully charged, the session ends and the charger communicates to the car that the lock can be released.

@Jake Minnie That's a 350 mile round trip. That's not something that people do all the time.

I do a 100 mile commute "all of the time" meaning many days a week. How many days a week did you do the Seattle to Portland and back drive?

Or was that just a couple of times a year?

@NixViridian Wyoming, as expected, is a little sparse when it comes to chargers but from a quick look at Chargehub, which lists most of the chargers out there - but not all, there are chargers at Casper and at Cheyenne. Typically, where you have a town that's at a junction of a freeway and a highway there'll be chargers - that's typically how things start. There are chargers at Douglas, Wheatland and Laramie between Casper and Cheyenne and several towns north of Casper have chargers too - I'm guessing you like north of Casper as it's closer to you than Cheyenne.

A lot of vehicles now can do more than 250+ miles, so that 140 miles round trip to Casper wouldn't be an issue. Do the trip, come home, put it on a L2 charger and 4 hours later and you're back at full charge. 218 miles, if you have something like a Chevy Bolt would be doable, as long as you didn't cruise at 90mph all the way. The 280ish mile range may be reduced by excessive speed enough to make that 218 miles a bit on the tight side. at 80, it shouldn't be that bad - but there are chargers.

Chargers tend not to be as visible as gas stations and tend to be closer to where other amenities are. Maybe when chargers go beyond the current 350kW that some can now achieve and charging times are below 10 minutes, this will change. Gas stations had to be visible because old cars didn't have GPS and touch screens to guide them. Now cars like Tesla's guide you to the best charging station and even precondition the battery for best charging time and to reduce wear on the battery.

@NixViridian I don't think that prices of electricity will increase much specifically due to EV charging. As it is, a typical two stage HVAC unit pulls more power from the grid when on the second stage than a L2 (33 miles of range per hour charge) car charger would do at home.

You don't even need to buy a L2 charger that connects to a 240V outlet if your typical car usage is under 50 miles a day. A lot of the time I'll connect my standard 110V charger to my car and essentially trickle charge it overnight at a whopping 4 miles of charge per hour. Here we get cheap rate from 11pm at night until 3pm the following afternoon. That 110V charger pulls far less power than appliances such as a hairdryer or a kettle. Mine pulls 11.5A - so less than the 1,300 watts the wife's hairdryer pulls.

Even if you only do 30 to 50 miles per day and then every once in a while you go to Casper or Cheyenne you could make sure you're topped off before you go and maybe grab a charger on your way back to reduce the at-home charging time when you return.
